{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2016}} {{Infobox U.S. legislation | name = Mental Health Systems Act of 1980 | fullname = A bill to improve the provision of mental health services and otherwise promote mental health throughout the United States; and for other purposes. | acronym = MHSA | nickname = | enacted by = 96th | effective date = | public law url = http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/granule/STATUTE-94/STATUTE-94-Pg1564/content-detail.html | cite public law = Pub.L. 96-398 | cite statutes at large = | acts amended = [[Community Mental Health Act|Community Mental Health Centers Act]], [[Public Health Service Act]], [[Social Security Act]] | title amended = 42 | sections created = {{USC|42|9401|9523}} | sections amended = {{USC|42|210}}, {{USCSec|42|225a}}, {{USCSec|42|242a}}, {{USCSec|42|300m}}, {{USCSec|42|1396b}}, {{USCSec|42|2689}} | leghisturl = http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.uscongress/legislation.96s1177 | introducedin = Senate | introducedbill = {{USBill|96|S.|1177}} | introducedby = [[Ted Kennedy]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]–[[Massachusetts|MA]]) | introduceddate = May 17, 1979 | committees = | passedbody1 = | passeddate1 = | passedvote1 = | passedbody2 = | passeddate2 = | passedvote2 = | conferencedate = | passedbody3 = | passeddate3 = | passedvote3 = | passedbody4 = | passeddate4 = | passedvote4 = | signedpresident = [[Jimmy Carter]] | signeddate = October 7, 1980 }}
'''The Mental Health Systems Act of 1980''' (MHSA) was [[United States]] legislation signed by President [[Jimmy Carter]] which provided grants to community mental health centers. During the following [[Ronald Reagan]] administration, the [[United States Congress]] repealed most of the law.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Matt|title=Cook County Jail, America's Largest Mental Hospital is a Jail|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2015/06/americas-largest-mental-hospital-is-a-jail/395012/|accessdate=2015-09-13|work=The Atlantic|date=June 8, 2015}}</ref> The MHSA was considered landmark legislation in mental health care policy.
==History== Coinciding with a movement during the 1970s for rehabilitation of people with severe mental illnesses, the Mental Health Systems Act supported and financed community mental health support systems, which coordinated general health care, mental health care, and social support services.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Goldman|first1=H. H.|last2=Morrissey|first2=J. P.|last3=Ridgely|first3=M. S.|last4=Frank|first4=R. G.|last5=Newman|first5=S. J.|last6=Kennedy|first6=C.|title=Lessons on the program on chronic mental illness|journal=Health Affairs|date=August 1992|volume=11|issue=3|pages=51–68|pmid=1398453|doi=10.1377/hlthaff.11.3.51|url=http://content.healthaffairs.org/content/11/3/51.full.pdf|accessdate=2015-09-13}}</ref> The law followed the 1978 Report of the [[President's Commission on Mental Health]], which made recommendations for improving mental health care in the United States. While some concerns existed about the methodology followed by the President's Committee, the report served as the foundation for the MHSA, which in turn was seen as landmark legislation in U.S. mental health policy.<ref name=Thomas>{{cite journal|last1=Thomas|first1=Alexander|title=Ronald Reagan and the Commitment of the Mentally Ill: Capital, Interest Groups, and the Eclipse of Social Policy|journal=Electronic Journal of Sociology|date=1998|volume=3|issue=4|url=http://sociology.org/content/vol003.004/thomas_d.html}}</ref>
The Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1981, signed by President [[Ronald Reagan]] on August 13, 1981, repealed most of the MHSA. The [[U.S. patients' bill of rights|Patients' Bill of Rights]], section 501, was not repealed; per Congressional record, the Congress felt that state provisions were sufficient and section 501 served as a recommendation to states to review and refine existing policies.<ref name=lyon-levine>{{cite journal|last1=Lyon-Levine|first1=Martha|last2=Levine|first2=Martin|last3=Zusman|first3=Jack|title=Developments in Patients' Bill of Rights Since the Mental Health Systems Act|journal=Mental and Physical Disability Law Reporter|date=March 1985|volume=9|issue=2|url=http://law.usc.edu/assets/docs/Developments_in_Patients.pdf|accessdate=2015-09-13}}</ref>
