'''Ottoi Călin''' (March 1886 - April 1, 1917) was a [[Romania]]n physician, journalist and [[Socialism|socialist]] militant, considered one of the [[Theoretician (Marxism)|theoreticians]] of the [[Labour movement in Romania|Romanian workers' movement]] during the early 20th century.

==Early life and education==
Călin was born in a poor [[History of the Jews in Romania|Jewish]] family in [[Iaşi]], in north-eastern Romania. After finishing high school, he obtained a medical degree from the [[Grigore T. Popa University of Medicine and Pharmacy|local university]]. During his teen years, along with other young students, he frequented the ''Circle of Social Studies'' organized by socialists [[Leon Ghelerter]] and [[Max Vexler]]. The ''Circle'', the main left-wing association in [[Moldavia]] at the time, played a major role in shaping future leaders of the Romanian socialist movement, such as [[Mihail Gheorghiu Bujor]] and [[Ilie Moscovici]].{{sfn|Petrescu|n.d.|p=162}}{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=177}} Beside participating in the ''Circle'', Călin lectured on [[Natural sciences|natural]] and [[social science]]s for a local [[Adult education|adult school]]. Beginning with 1908, he published regularly in the ''[[Viitorul Social]]'' magazine, with his articles targeting primarily theoretical and tactical issues. Among his noted contributions of the time are a brief biography on [[Karl Marx]], providing an analysis of the latter's contributions to the development of [[scientific socialism]], and a history of the [[Paris Commune]], presented as a proof of the viability of [[Communist society|proletarian rule]]. During the same period, Călin also worked towards the establishment of a socialist youth organization. In 1910 he was one of the representatives of the Iaşi socialists at the Congress that formalised the creation of the [[Social Democratic Party of Romania (1910-1918)|Social Democratic Party]] (PSD).{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=178}}

After graduating in 1911, with the support of fellow party-members, Călin left for Western Europe in order to further his medical studies. Following a brief stay in [[Berlin]], he arrived in [[Paris]], where he joined the existing Romanian socialist group comprising, among others, [[Christian Rakovsky]], [[Ioan Sion (politician)|Ioan Sion]] and [[Barbu Lăzăreanu]]. Călin used the occasion to forge relations with the [[French Section of the Workers' International|local socialist party]]. Continuing his theoretical pursuits, he was particularly influenced by the ideas [[Jean Jaurès]], embracing [[pacifism]].{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=180}}

==Activism and war==
Returning to Romania, Călin settled in [[Bucharest]] and practised medicine, specializing as an [[Internal medicine|internist]]. At the same time he continued his journalistic activity, writing for ''Viitorul Social'' and ''[[România Muncitoare]]'', and lectured on the [[History of socialism|history of socialist doctrines]] for the ''Socialist School'' set up by the party in Romania's capital.{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=180}} Along with many of the leading party members, Călin was one of the founding members of ''Casa Poporului'', a [[cooperative|cooperative society]] established in October 1914 in order to manage the various party headquarters across Romania.{{sfn|Petrescu|n.d.|p=231}} As a recognition for his efforts, in 1913, the Executive Committee of the PSD designated him as the [[editor in chief]] of the second series of ''Viitorul Social'', position he would hold until 1915.{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=179}} The main responsible with the magazine's columns on the international socialist movement, he also continued to contribute articles on major theoretical themes, such as [[Parliamentary system|parliamentarism]], the [[universal vote]], and the [[Opposition to World War I|socialist attitude towards the war]] . Around this time, he also held, under the pseudonym ''Ioan Otescu'', the weekly medical column in ''[[Seara (newspaper)|Seara]]'', and published research articles in ''Higiena'', concentrating on [[Social determinants of health in poverty|illnesses prevalent among the poor]].{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=180}} Furthermore, Călin translated [[Maxim Gorky|Gorky]]'s [[The Mother (1906 novel)|The Mother]] and, along with Bujor, [[Karl Kautsky]]'s commentary on the [[Erfurt Program]].{{sfn|Petrescu|n.d.|p=93}}

[[File:Romanian socialists, 1915.jpg|thumb|left|260px|Călin (middle row, sixth from left) and other leaders of the Romanian Social Democratic Party at the 60th anniversary of [[Constantin Dobrogeanu-Gherea]] (1915)]]
A delegate to the 1914 PSD Congress, Călin advocated a more militant party position on the [[Land reform in Romania|agrarian issue]], and was decisive in the adoption of [[neutrality (international relations)|neutrality]] as the party's stance towards [[World War I]]. In October 1915, at the Extraordinary PSD Congress, he prepared the main report, which commented on the attitude of the European socialist movement towards the war. The report, critical of the Bureau of the [[Second International]], adopted the [[antimilitarism|anti-militarist]] stance of the first [[Zimmerwald Conference]],{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|pp=180-181}} while at the same time providing that, were Romania to join the war, the socialists would take no action that would damage the government.{{sfn|Liveanu|1960|pp=114-115}} The report was approved by a large majority. At the same Congress, Călin was also elected to the party's Executive Committee, along with [[Ecaterina Arbore]], [[Alecu Constantinescu]], [[Gheorghe Cristescu]], [[I.C. Frimu]], [[Dimitrie Marinescu]], and [[Christian Rakovsky]]. During the following months, he took part in the organisation of various anti-war protests across the country.{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=181}}

In the second part of 1916, as [[Romania in World War I|Romania joined the war]] on the side of the [[Allies of World War I|Entente]], Călin was drafted as a [[combat medic]], and was later assigned to the [[military ambulance]]. Retreating to Moldavia along with the whole Romanian Army, he contracted [[Epidemic typhus|typhus]] during the epidemic that ravaged the region during the war. Transported to Iaşi for treatment, he died there in early April 1917.{{sfn|Popescu-Puţuri|Georgescu|1971|p=182}} Over one thousand workers and socialists were present on {{OldStyleDate|April 16||April 3}} at his burial, which became the first major socialist public gathering in Romania after the start of the war. The manifestation, and especially the anti-war eulogy given by Bujor, which called on the Romanian workers to follow the example of the [[February Revolution|anti-monarchic revolution]] in [[Russia]], resulted in a major crack-down by the authorities on the renascent socialist movement in Moldavia.{{sfn|Liveanu|1956|p=21}}

